You are right. More precise wording:

```text
This is a B2Boost post-login URL.

Flow:

1. The user selects a sales point on the Arthur Core page and clicks the confirmation button.

2. Arthur Core receives the confirmation, creates a temporary one-time UUID handoff code, and sends the user to B2Boost using the configured B2Boost post-login URL:

   https://<B2Boost-url>/post-login?code=<handoff-code-or-UUID>

3. B2Boost then calls Arthur Core server-to-server using that code:

   POST https://<arthur-core-url>/auth/handoff/exchange

   Request body:
   {
     "code": "<handoff-code-or-UUID>"
   }

4. Arthur Core validates the code. If valid, Arthur Core returns the security context to B2Boost.

Important: the browser only carries the temporary UUID code. The full security context is returned only through the server-to-server exchange.
```

Even though the trigger is the **confirmation button**, technically Arthur still performs an HTTP redirect/navigation to the B2Boost URL after creating the UUID.
